body:
I would do a borderless window. This is slightly different in coding

``` c
// GLFW_FLOATING was not necessary for me in Windows 8.1 but might be for others
// The documentation also says that GLFW_FLOATING is primarily for debugging purposes
glfwWindowHint(GLFW_FLOATING, GL_TRUE);
glfwWindowHint(GLFW_DECORATED, GL_FALSE);
window = glfwCreateWindow(mode->width, mode->height, "Simple example", NULL, NULL);
```

Two notes for the behaviour you want
1) There is no way for you to stop the taskbar from showing without also forcing other applications to be hidden. This is because the taskbar is essentially "always-on-top." 
2) They would need to kill your application to access other programs. This could be incredibly bad especially for people who do not have multi monitor setups.
